<i>'Cause the writing's on</i>

78
00:16:33,201 --> 00:16:38,873
<i>The wall</i>

79
00:16:43,336 --> 00:16:46,256
Start anywhere you like.

80
00:16:46,381 --> 00:16:48,383
Take your time, 007,
but in five minutes

81
00:16:48,466 --> 00:16:49,718
the head of
the Joint Security Service

82
00:16:49,759 --> 00:16:51,011
is going to walk
through that door,

83
00:16:51,052 --> 00:16:52,262
and I've got
to explain to him

84
00:16:52,345 --> 00:16:55,598
how one of our agents decided to
potter off to Mexico, all on his own,

85
00:16:55,682 --> 00:16:57,392
and cause
an international incident.

86
00:16:57,434 --> 00:16:59,686
With all due respect, sir,
it could've been worse.

87
00:16:59,728 --> 00:17:01,813
Worse? You blew up
half a bloody block.

88
00:17:01,896 --> 00:17:04,399
Well, better half a block than
a whole stadium full of people.

89
00:17:04,733 --> 00:17:06,568
You had no authority.

90
00:17:07,235 --> 00:17:08,236
None.

91
00:17:08,319 --> 00:17:10,447
As you know,
we're in the middle
of the biggest shakeup

92
00:17:10,530 --> 00:17:12,073
in the history of
British intelligence.

93
00:17:12,157 --> 00:17:14,909
The ink's barely dry
on this merger with MI5

94
00:17:14,993 --> 00:17:16,786
and already they're itching
for a chance to scrap

95
00:17:16,870 --> 00:17:18,496
the double-0 program forever.

96
00:17:18,580 --> 00:17:20,874
And you've just
given them one.

97
00:17:21,624 --> 00:17:23,293
You're right, sir.

98
00:17:23,626 --> 00:17:26,004
You have got
a tricky day ahead.

99
00:17:28,882 --> 00:17:31,092
This is an official question.

100
00:17:32,260 --> 00:17:35,430
Mexico City.
What were you doing there?

101
00:17:36,264 --> 00:17:40,060
It was just a coincidence.
I was taking some overdue holiday.

102
00:17:41,644 --> 00:17:43,271
Okay. Fine.

103
00:17:43,938 --> 00:17:46,608
As of this morning,
you are officially grounded.

104
00:17:46,649 --> 00:17:50,320
I'm standing you down from
all operations indefinitely.

105
00:17:58,536 --> 00:18:00,080
Very good, sir.

106
00:18:00,997 --> 00:18:02,415
007?

107
00:18:03,958 --> 00:18:05,001
Sir?

108
00:18:05,627 --> 00:18:06,836
I don't know what
you're playing at,

109
00:18:06,920 --> 00:18:09,547
but whatever it is,
it has to stop.

110
00:18:09,631 --> 00:18:10,632
Now.

111
00:18:12,967 --> 00:18:15,136
- So sorry.
- Am I interrupting?
Not remotely.

112
00:18:15,220 --> 00:18:17,180
007, I'd like you
to meet Max Denbigh,

113
00:18:17,263 --> 00:18:18,640
head of the Joint
Security Service.

114
00:18:18,723 --> 00:18:21,434
It's a pleasure to finally meet you, 007.
I've heard a lot about you.

115
00:18:21,476 --> 00:18:22,644
Most of it good.

116
00:18:22,727 --> 00:18:24,187
Congratulations
on your new appointment.

117
00:18:24,270 --> 00:18:25,271
Thank you.

118
00:18:25,313 --> 00:18:26,815
I suppose we should
call you C now.

119
00:18:26,898 --> 00:18:28,817
No, no. "Max," please.

120
00:18:29,359 --> 00:18:31,486
No, I think
I'll call you C,

121
00:18:31,528 --> 00:18:32,529
C.

122
00:18:33,154 --> 00:18:34,823
As you wish.

123
00:18:34,864 --> 00:18:38,660
Well, my door is always
open, 007, for my employees.

124
00:18:39,828 --> 00:18:41,663
This merger's gonna be
a whole new chapter for us.

125
00:18:41,704 --> 00:18:45,416
We're going to bring British
intelligence out of the Dark Ages

126
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:47,085
into the light.

127
00:18:48,795 --> 00:18:50,296
That all sounds lovely.

128
00:18:50,338 --> 00:18:53,508
That'll be all, 007.
Report to Q tomorrow
for medical, thank you.

129
00:18:54,008 --> 00:18:55,343
Very good, sir.

130
00:18:55,510 --> 00:18:56,678
(DOOR OPENS)

131
00:18:57,804 --> 00:18:58,930
(DOOR CLOSES)

132
00:19:05,228 --> 00:19:06,437
James?

133
00:19:06,521 --> 00:19:07,522
Moneypenny.

134
00:19:07,730 --> 00:19:10,191
So? How was
the meeting?

135
00:19:10,233 --> 00:19:12,026
Very good,
thank you.

136
00:19:12,402 --> 00:19:13,486
Here.

137
00:19:13,528 --> 00:19:15,697
- Forensics finally released this.
- What is it?

138
00:19:15,738 --> 00:19:18,783
It's personal effects
they recovered from Skyfall.

139
00:19:18,867 --> 00:19:20,702
Perfect. You can
bring it to me later.

140
00:19:20,743 --> 00:19:23,204
- What do you mean?
- My place, 9:00.

141
00:19:29,544 --> 00:19:30,879
(DOORBELL BEEPS)

142
00:19:35,550 --> 00:19:36,885
Evening.

143
00:19:36,926 --> 00:19:38,178
Come in.

144
00:19:40,138 --> 00:19:41,973
Have you just moved in?

145
00:19:42,056 --> 00:19:43,057
No.

146
00:19:43,892 --> 00:19:45,351
Well, I like what you've
done with the place.

147
00:19:47,270 --> 00:19:48,771
Your delivery.

148
00:19:49,772 --> 00:19:51,232
Thank you.

149
00:19:54,319 --> 00:19:55,445
Would you like a drink?

150
00:19:55,820 --> 00:19:57,071
No, thanks.
I'm not staying.

151
00:19:57,155 --> 00:19:58,323
That's a shame.

152
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:00,950
What's going on, James?

153
00:20:01,034 --> 00:20:02,118
(SIGHS)

154
00:20:02,202 --> 00:20:05,496
There's not one person at MI6
who isn't talking about it.

155
00:20:05,580 --> 00:20:08,208
Talking about what, exactly?

156
00:20:09,209 --> 00:20:12,045
That what you did in Mexico
was one step too far.

157
00:20:12,921 --> 00:20:14,797
That you're finished.

158
00:20:14,881 --> 00:20:16,257
And what do you think?

159
00:20:16,591 --> 00:20:18,760
I think you're just
getting started.

160
00:20:20,178 --> 00:20:22,096
I don't know what you mean.

161
00:20:22,263 --> 00:20:23,598
All right.

162
00:20:24,849 --> 00:20:26,976
I think you've got a secret.

163
00:20:27,769 --> 00:20:30,605
And it's something
you won't tell anyone.

164
00:20:31,481 --> 00:20:33,483
Because you
don't trust anyone.

165
00:20:44,285 --> 00:20:48,248
<i>If anything happens to me, 007,
I need you to do something.</i>

166
00:20:48,581 --> 00:20:52,085
<i>Find a man
called Marco Sciarra.</i>

167
00:20:53,169 --> 00:20:54,504
<i>Kill him.</i>

168
00:20:55,213 --> 00:20:57,298
<i>And don't miss the funeral.</i>

169
00:21:00,468 --> 00:21:01,803
Jesus.

170
00:21:02,679 --> 00:21:04,138
Where did you get it?

171
00:21:04,222 --> 00:21:06,724
In my mailbox
just after she died.

172
00:21:07,433 --> 00:21:09,602
Well, she was never
short of surprises.

173
00:21:10,937 --> 00:21:13,189
She wasn't gonna let death
get in the way of her job.

174
00:21:15,149 --> 00:21:17,568
I've been tracking
Sciarra ever since.

175
00:21:17,652 --> 00:21:18,987
And what have you found?

176
00:21:19,487 --> 00:21:21,406
Nothing significant yet.

177
00:21:21,864 --> 00:21:22,907
When's the funeral?

178
00:21:23,825 --> 00:21:26,202
Three days. In Rome.

179
00:21:26,286 --> 00:21:29,289
If you think M's signing off on
that, you're insane.

180
00:21:29,539 --> 00:21:30,873
He won't let you
out of his sight.

181
00:21:30,957 --> 00:21:33,167
Yes, it's a bit of
a problem.

182
00:21:33,376 --> 00:21:34,585
Listen.

183
00:21:35,044 --> 00:21:37,964
Could you do a little
quiet digging for me?

184
00:21:38,381 --> 00:21:41,009
I heard a name in Mexico.
"The Pale King."

185
00:21:43,428 --> 00:21:45,305
You want me
to be your mole.

186
00:21:47,056 --> 00:21:48,099
Yes.

187
00:21:50,226 --> 00:21:53,229
And what makes you think
you can trust me?

188
00:21:55,857 --> 00:21:57,191
Instinct.

189
00:22:57,752 --> 00:23:00,922
TANNER: Poor old girl.
Rigged for demolition in a week.

190
00:23:02,340 --> 00:23:05,176
Cheaper to knock her down
than to rebuild.

191
00:23:05,593 --> 00:23:06,928
Still.

192
00:23:07,011 --> 00:23:09,514
Time waits for no man
and all that.

193
00:23:10,348 --> 00:23:13,267
Anyway, all the money's
been spent on this,

194
00:23:14,185 --> 00:23:16,854
the New Centre for
National Security.

195
00:23:18,689 --> 00:23:20,691
BOND: So that's C's new digs.

196
00:23:21,025 --> 00:23:22,527
You've met him, have you?

197
00:23:22,610 --> 00:23:24,779
Yesterday.
What do we know about him?

198
00:23:24,821 --> 00:23:26,989
Classic Whitehall mandarin.

199
00:23:27,073 --> 00:23:28,241
Wrote a dossier last year

200
00:23:28,282 --> 00:23:30,284
on how the double-0 program
was obsolete,

201
00:23:30,368 --> 00:23:33,371
how drones could do
all our dirty work abroad.

202
00:23:33,704 --> 00:23:35,248
Went to school with
the Home Secretary.

203
00:23:35,289 --> 00:23:36,791
Of course, he did.

204
00:23:36,874 --> 00:23:39,127
This merger's
just the start of it.

205
00:23:39,210 --> 00:23:41,587
In three days, there's a security
conference in Tokyo

206
00:23:41,629 --> 00:23:43,923
to decide
the New World Order.

207
00:23:43,965 --> 00:23:46,175
If C gets his way,
he'll have unlimited access

208
00:23:46,259 --> 00:23:48,970
to the combined intelligence
streams of nine countries.

209
00:23:49,053 --> 00:23:50,304
Including us.

210
00:23:50,346 --> 00:23:51,514
Quite.

211
00:24:00,815 --> 00:24:03,151
Well, a lot's happened
while you were away.

212
00:24:03,234 --> 00:24:07,321
A train bombing in Hamburg and an
industrial explosion in Tunisia.

213
00:24:07,488 --> 00:24:08,823
It's not great timing
for us.

214
00:24:09,240 --> 00:24:11,784
It's all rather
playing into C's hands.

215
00:24:11,826 --> 00:24:15,746
M, well, let's say
he's feeling the pressure.

216
00:24:16,205 --> 00:24:17,498
Yeah, I've noticed.

217
00:24:17,582 --> 00:24:19,375
Now, this way, 007.

218
00:24:19,459 --> 00:24:21,961
Be careful.
It's a trifle slippery.

219
00:24:24,839 --> 00:24:27,175
Q wasn't exactly feeling
at home in Whitehall,

220
00:24:27,216 --> 00:24:28,217
what with the new merger,

221
00:24:28,301 --> 00:24:32,430
so he set up shop here,
away from prying eyes,
as it were.

222
00:24:32,513 --> 00:24:35,349
I hear he's got something
rather special planned for you.

223
00:24:35,433 --> 00:24:37,101
I can hardly wait.

224
00:24:47,820 --> 00:24:48,988
Ah, 007.

225
00:24:50,448 --> 00:24:52,533
- Q.
- Q: Please excuse the mess.

226
00:24:52,909 --> 00:24:54,118
Everything's a little
bit up in the air,

227
00:24:54,202 --> 00:24:55,453
what with the changes
and all.

228
00:24:55,536 --> 00:24:57,872
Couple of things
to get through.

229
00:24:58,831 --> 00:25:00,541
Shall we get started?

230
00:25:01,167 --> 00:25:02,502
Just relax.

231
00:25:04,337 --> 00:25:05,338
That's it. Lovely.

232
00:25:05,630 --> 00:25:07,507
Now, you may feel a small...

233
00:25:07,548 --> 00:25:08,591
Christ!

234
00:25:09,008 --> 00:25:10,009
...prick.

235
00:25:12,220 --> 00:25:13,304
What is it?

236
00:25:13,387 --> 00:25:15,097
Q: Cutting-edge
nanotechnology.

237
00:25:15,389 --> 00:25:16,807
Smart Blood.

238
00:25:18,017 --> 00:25:20,019
Microchips in
your bloodstream.

239
00:25:20,061 --> 00:25:23,147
Allows us to track
your movements in the field.

240
00:25:23,856 --> 00:25:25,525
You see those readouts?

241
00:25:25,566 --> 00:25:29,237
We can monitor your vital signs
from anywhere on the planet.

242
00:25:29,320 --> 00:25:31,447
Well, that sounds marvelous.

243
00:25:31,864 --> 00:25:34,700
Call it a post-Mexico
insurance policy.

244
00:25:34,742 --> 00:25:36,285
By direct order of M.

245
00:25:38,162 --> 00:25:40,248
I completely understand.

246
00:25:41,791 --> 00:25:42,917
Good.

247
00:25:44,752 --> 00:25:47,922
Right. Well, I've just, um,
got one last thing for you

248
00:25:47,964 --> 00:25:49,507
and you can be on your way.

249
00:25:56,430 --> 00:25:58,349
Magnificent, isn't she?

250
00:25:58,766 --> 00:26:01,060
Zero to 60 in
three point two seconds.

251
00:26:01,102 --> 00:26:04,480
Fully bulletproof.
A few little tricks up her sleeve.

252
00:26:05,481 --> 00:26:07,275
It's a shame, really.
She was meant for you,

253
00:26:07,316 --> 00:26:10,236
but she's been
reassigned to 009.

254
00:26:11,529 --> 00:26:13,406
But you can have this.

255
00:26:18,953 --> 00:26:20,580
Does it do anything?

256
00:26:20,621 --> 00:26:22,290
It tells the time.

257
